In case the diff of a PR is pretty big it would ease the review process if all headers and sidebars etc could be hidden when doing the review with some button/shortcut.

I created a small bookmarklet for myself to have the diff bigger:
{code:java}
javascript:(function(){ jQuery('.changes').parent().css('height', 'calc(100vh - 30px)'); jQuery('html, body').animate({ scrollTop: $(document).height()-$(window).height() }, 'slow'); })();
{code}
But this might not work anymore for future versions and is not available for everybody.

An out-of-the-box solution for this would be highly appreciated.

Best, Alex

Currently, we have the following REST endpoints for pull-request settings:
h4. Project
/rest/api/1.0/projects/<project key>/settings/pull-requests/<scmID>
h4. Repository
/rest/api/1.0/projects/<project key>/repos/<repo slug>/settings/pull-requests

However, the following attributes are missing from the response object returned by the Project endpoint:
{noformat}
"requiredAllApprovers": false,
  "requiredApprovers": 0,
  "requiredAllTasksComplete": false,
  "requiredSuccessfulBuilds": 0,
  "unapproveOnUpdate": true
{noformat}
and
{noformat}
  "com.atlassian.bitbucket.server.bitbucket-bundled-hooks:requiredApprovers": {
    "enable": false,
    "count": 0
  },
  "com.atlassian.bitbucket.server.bitbucket-build:requiredBuilds": {
    "enable": false,
    "count": 0
  },
{noformat}

If the above attributes are configured only at Project level (and hence inherited by its repositories), then it is desirable to have them returned for Projects too.

h3. Issue Summary
When editing a comment with markdown code, the highlighting is working, but once the comment is saved, all highlighting is gone. See attached picture for reference.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Step 1: Add a comment in the pull request like the below:
{code}
``` C++
auto powerEnable = isi->GetTisPowerEnable().lock();
if (powerEnable) {
    *powerEnable = false;
    *powerEnable = true;
}
```
{code}
You see some of the word highlighted before you post the comment.
 # Step 2
When you click on the Comment button, you see that the syntax highlighting is gone.
h3. Expected Results
The syntax highlighting should remain after the comment is posted
h3. Actual Results
The syntax highlighting is gone after the comment is posted even though it shows up while drafting the comment


h3. Workaround

Use a different alias for the code highlighting mode as defined in [CodeMirror's codebase|https://github.com/codemirror/CodeMirror/blob/master/mode/meta.js] (look if the highlighting mode you need has an alias, if it does, use one of the listed aliases). For instance in the noted case above, a working highlighting mode is {{cpp}}.

h3. Issue Summary

Unable to reset the value of a repository description afterwards to an empty string using the REST API.
h3. Steps to Reproduce

*Step 1*: Use the REST API query to set a description for a repository to something like 'test':
{code:sql}
curl -u admin:admin -v -X PUT -d '{ "description": "test" }' -H "Content-Type: application/json" http://localhost:7990/rest/api/1.0/projects/FIR/repos/new-repo
{code}
Response:
{code:sql}
{"slug":"new-repo","id":13,"name":"new-repo","description":"test","scmId":"git","state":"AVAILABLE","statusMessage":"Available","forkable":false,"project":{"key":"FIR","id":1,"name":"first","public":false,"type":"NORMAL","links":{"self":[{"href":"http://localhost:7990/projects/FIR"}]}},"public":true,"links":{"clone":[{"href":"http://localhost:7990/scm/fir/new-repo.git","name":"http"},{"href":"ssh://git@localhost:7999/fir/new-repo.git","name":"ssh"}],"self":[{"href":"http://localhost:7990/projects/FIR/repos/new-repo/browse"}]}}*
{code}
*Step 2*: Now try to change this to a null value using the following:
{code:sql}
curl -u admin:admin -v -X PUT -d '{ "description": "" }' -H "Content-Type: application/json" http://localhost:7990/rest/api/1.0/projects/FIR/repos/new-repo
{code}
Response:
{code:sql}
{"slug":"new-repo","id":13,"name":"new-repo","description":"test","scmId":"git","state":"AVAILABLE","statusMessage":"Available","forkable":false,"project":{"key":"FIR","id":1,"name":"first","public":false,"type":"NORMAL","links":{"self":[{"href":"http://localhost:7990/projects/FIR"}]}},"public":true,"links":{"clone":[{"href":"http://localhost:7990/scm/fir/new-repo.git","name":"http"},{"href":"ssh://git@localhost:7999/fir/new-repo.git","name":"ssh"}],"self":[{"href":"http://localhost:7990/projects/FIR/repos/new-repo/browse"}]}}*
{code}
h3. Expected Results

It should change it to a null value, that is, the description of the repository should be reset to empty.
h3. Actual Results
{code:sql}
curl -u admin:admin -v -X PUT -d '{ "description": "" }' -H "Content-Type: application/json" http://localhost:7990/rest/api/1.0/projects/FIR/repos/new-repo
{code}
Response:
{code:sql}
{"slug":"new-repo","id":13,"name":"new-repo","description":"test","scmId":"git","state":"AVAILABLE","statusMessage":"Available","forkable":false,"project":{"key":"FIR","id":1,"name":"first","public":false,"type":"NORMAL","links":{"self":[{"href":"http://localhost:7990/projects/FIR"}]}},"public":true,"links":{"clone":[{"href":"http://localhost:7990/scm/fir/new-repo.git","name":"http"},{"href":"ssh://git@localhost:7999/fir/new-repo.git","name":"ssh"}],"self":[{"href":"http://localhost:7990/projects/FIR/repos/new-repo/browse"}]}}*
{code}
the description is still “test”, which means that when you pass an empty value it is ignored. This happens for ” ” null and well anything that is not actual text.
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available. Can use the Bitbucket UI instead to change the description.

Current "tipsy" popup on the page where I can see the list of comments is pretty short. Lots of developers are using 80 column hard wrapped git commit descriptions in their repositories. If using such notation, then the tipsy popup looks like this:

 

!image-2020-10-14-15-46-41-374.png!

 

After changing the width of this popup to at least 80 characters, the popup looks much better:

 

!image-2020-10-14-15-48-32-305.png!

 

I think it would be better for Bitbucket to increase the .tipsy-inner's size from 56 characters to 80 characters.

As a workaround, user can use plugins like Stylus or Greasemonkey to hot-patch the CSS:

{code:css}
    .tipsy .tipsy-inner {
        max-width: 80ch !important;
    }
{code}

but I'm not sure if there's any reason why this shouldn't be the default?

h3. Issue Summary

The messages returned by REST API requests differ accordingly to the access level the user has on the system and sometimes revealing some details that can be used on an account enumeration attack.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# execute a POST request to Bitbucket (endpoint kept out for security reasons)

h3. Expected Results
In both cases the messages should be generic with no details to prevent an attacker inferring if a user exists or not and if permissions it lack permissions.

Example: 
{noformat}
You are not permitted to access the application/resource due to AuthenticationException or AuthorisationException
{noformat}

h3. Actual Results

- Scenario #1 User with no permission 
{code:json}
{"context":null,"message":"You are not permitted to access this resource","exceptionName":"com.atlassian.bitbucket.AuthorisationException"}]
{code}

- Scenario #2 User does not exist
{code:json}
{"context":null,"message":"Authentication failed. Please check your credentials and try again.","exceptionName":"com.atlassian.bitbucket.auth.IncorrectPasswordAuthenticationException"}]}
{code}

h3. Workaround
No workaround available at the moment

While Bitbucket is able to work with LFS objects stored externally, it however, doesn't have the ability to recognize the availability of the files. The UI shows that the file is not present when we are in either the {{Compare}} page or the Pull Request page. 
 !Screenshot 2020-09-22 at 7.01.47 PM.png|thumbnail! 

For example, if the LFS objects are stored in a Jfrog Artifactory, it is tracked in Git LFS and the repository has a .lfsconfig file pointing to the Artifactory repository. When viewing the compare page on the UI, Bitbucket is unable to find the file in the local LFS storage and throws a 404 error with the following line logged:
{code:java}
{"objects":[{"oid":"d638dd7b5cd219ad8bc138dbe54245a65593f32fa56330542f157a52e7728c49","size":70144,"error":{"message":"Object does not exist on the server","code":404}}]}
{code}

This can be misleading to end users as they will think the file has been deleted on the server, when in actual fact, it is stored outside of Bitbucket in Artifactory (using Git LFS) and cannot be compared. 

Bitbucket should be able to recognize that the files are in an external object storage and link them when in the Compare page.
